Part One: Introduction

  • The goal of this project is to figure out what (approximately) $300,000 CAD can get you in the Canadian real estate market in (May-June) 2023. It will also serve as a benchmark and record of data to compare against in the coming years.
  • The main data source will be realtor.ca and will be scraped using selenium, as well as undetected_chromedriver and ProtonVPN to avoid any issues.
  • Locations of interest will be based on the population of provinces/territories and their largest municipality.
  • To start, the listings in the following locations will be scraped:
    • Toronto, ON
    • Montreal, QC
    • Vancouver, BC
    • Calgary, AB
    • Winnipeg, MB
    • Saskatoon, SK
    • Halifax, NS

Hypotheses

  • The average house price in Canada in April 2023 was $716,000. However, the average price varies quite significantly depending on location. As such, it is likely that a $300,000 house is still possible, but only in 'less than ideal' locations.
  • Most likely, you can only get a semi-decent condo or apartment in that price range, but not in areas like Vancouver or Toronto. If there are listings in that price range in Vancouver or Toronto, there may be other issues or conditions that make it 'less than ideal'.
  • With condos/apartment, monthly fees should be factored into price considerations as well. Annual property taxes is another factor.
  • Per Canada's Immigration Levels Plan 2023-2025, there may be a sharp increase in the number of immigrants in the coming years. The vast majority will likely go to either Toronto or Vancouver (and surrounding areas), meaning rent and housing costs will likely increase quite significantly in the coming years.
  • Quebec's stance is currently to reject Trudeau's immigration plan, making it likely they will be less affected in terms of rent and housing cost increases. The other provinces will likely see an influx in immigrants as well, perhaps to a lesser extent than Toronto and Vancouver, but there is still a strong likelihood prices will increase in the coming years, leading to reduced affordability.

Store in DataFrame

df = pd.DataFrame()
df["url"] = urls
df["inner_html"] = inner_htmls


def extract_data(t_inner_html):
    # --extract preview img--
    pattern = r'<img\s+.*?\bsrc="(.*?)"'
    matches = re.findall(pattern, t_inner_html)
    preview_img = matches[0]

    # --extract price--
    pattern = r"\$\d+(?:,\d+)*"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_inner_html)
    price = match.group()
    price_cad = int(price.replace("$", "").replace(",", ""))

    # --extract address-
    pattern = r'data-binding="innertext=Address">([^<]+)'
    match = re.search(pattern, t_inner_html)
    address = match.group(1)

    # --find number of beds/baths--
    pattern = r'data-binding="innertext=NumberVal">([^<]+)'
    matches = re.findall(pattern, t_inner_html)

    # search parameters filter out 0 beds/baths
    num_bedrooms = matches[0]
    num_bathrooms = matches[1]

    return preview_img, price_cad, address, num_bedrooms, num_bathrooms


df["data"] = df["inner_html"].apply(lambda x: extract_data(x))

df["preview"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[0])
df["price"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[1])
df["address"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[2])
df["bedrooms"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[3])
df["bathrooms"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[4])

# drop duplicates in address column
df = df.drop_duplicates(subset="address", keep="last")

def convert_to_int(t_val):
    """Clean up actual count of beds/baths - eg. (2+1)->3"""
    try:
        x = int(t_val)
    except ValueError:
        x = int(eval(t_val))
    return x


df["bedrooms"] = df["bedrooms"].apply(lambda x: convert_to_int(x))
df["bathrooms"] = df["bathrooms"].apply(lambda x: convert_to_int(x))

# export data if scraping the actual listings later
now = datetime.now()
formatted_date = now.strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M")

df[
    [
        "url",
        "preview",
        "price",
        "address",
        "bedrooms",
        "bathrooms",
    ]
].to_excel(f"{location_input.split(',')[0]}_{formatted_date}.xlsx", index=False)

driver.quit()

more_info = []

for t_url in properties_df_filtered["url"].tolist():
    driver = uc.Chrome()
    driver.get(t_url)

    # wait for page to load
    full_address = []

    while len(full_address) == 0:
        try:
            full_address = driver.find_elements(By.XPATH, '//*[@id="listingAddress"]')
        except:
            time.sleep(1)

    # get full address
    full_address = full_address[0].get_attribute("innerHTML").replace("<br>", ", ")

    # listing description
    listing_description = driver.find_elements(
        By.XPATH, '//*[@id="propertyDescriptionCon"]'
    )[0]
    listing_description = listing_description.get_attribute("innerHTML")

    listing_description = listing_description.strip()

    # property summary section - convert to dict
    summary = driver.find_elements(By.XPATH, '//*[@id="PropertySummary"]/div')[
        0
    ].get_attribute("innerHTML")

    regex_pattern = r">\s*(.*?)\s*<"
    matches = re.findall(regex_pattern, summary, flags=re.DOTALL)

    t_list = []
    for x in matches:
        if "class=" in x:
            y = x.split(">")[-1]
        else:
            y = x
        t_list.append(y)

    t_list = [x for x in t_list if len(x) > 0 and x != "(CAD)"]

    t_dict = {}
    for i in range(0, len(t_list), 2):
        t_dict[t_list[i]] = t_list[i + 1]

    summary_dict = t_dict

    # other details
    building_details = driver.find_elements(
        By.XPATH, '//*[@id="listingDetailsBuildingCon"]'
    )[0]
    building_details_html = building_details.get_attribute("innerHTML")
    regex_pattern = r">\s*(.*?)\s*<"
    matches = re.findall(regex_pattern, building_details_html, flags=re.DOTALL)
    other_details = "\n".join([x for x in matches if len(x) > 0])

    more_info.append([full_address, listing_description, summary_dict, other_details])

    driver.quit()

properties_df_filtered["more_info"] = more_info

concat_df = pd.concat(
    [properties_df_filtered, properties_df_filtered["more_info"].apply(pd.Series)],
    axis=1,
)
concat_df.columns = [
    "url",
    "preview",
    "price",
    "address",
    "bedrooms",
    "bathrooms",
    "more_info",
    "full_address",
    "description",
    "summary",
    "other_details",
]
del concat_df["more_info"]

def find_monthly_fees(t_str): 
    pattern = r"\$(.*?)\s*\((?:CAD)?\)"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_str)

    if match:
        price = match.group(1)
        return price 
    else:
        return 0

concat_df["other_fees1"] = concat_df["other_details"].apply(
    lambda x: find_monthly_fees(x)
)

def return_frequency_of_fee(t_str):
    pattern = r"\(CAD\)\s*(\w+)"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_str)

    try:
        word = match.group(1)
    except AttributeError:
        word = "N/A"

    return word


concat_df["other_fees1_freq"] = concat_df["other_details"].apply(
    lambda x: return_frequency_of_fee(x)
)

try:
    concat_df["other_fees1"] = concat_df["other_fees1"].astype(float)
except ValueError:
    concat_df["other_fees1"] = (
        concat_df["other_fees1"].str.replace(",", "").astype(float)
    )

concat_df["other_fees1"] = concat_df["other_fees1"].fillna(0)
concat_df["other_fees1_annual"] = concat_df["other_fees1"]

# may need to modify if there's frequency other than `Monthly`
# so far, there's only been `Monthly` or `N/A`
mask = concat_df["other_fees1_freq"] == "Monthly"
concat_df.loc[mask, "other_fees1_annual"] = (
    concat_df.loc[mask, "other_fees1_annual"] * 12
)

# limitations:
# - QC listings don't include annual property tax in the summary
# - possible inaccuracies re: tax amounts on some listings?
def find_annual_fee(t_dict):
    annual_fee = 0
    for x in list(t_dict.values()):
        if "$" in x:
            annual_fee = float(x.replace(",", "").replace("$", ""))

    return annual_fee


concat_df["annual_fee"] = concat_df["summary"].apply(lambda x: find_annual_fee(x))
concat_df.other_fees1_annual = concat_df.other_fees1_annual.astype(float)
concat_df.annual_fee = concat_df.annual_fee.astype(float)

concat_df["total_fee_monthly"] = (
    concat_df.other_fees1_annual + concat_df.annual_fee
) / 12

# export
now = datetime.now()
formatted_date = now.strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M")

concat_df.to_excel(f"{location_input.split(',')[0]}_{formatted_date}.xlsx", index=False)

            y=building_type_by_location.loc[mask, "Count"],

        col=1,
    )
    ctr += 1

Notes

  • As hypothesized, a house in the price range of approximately $300,000 is still possible in Canada, at least in Winnipeg and Saskatoon.
  • In Calgary, you can get a (probably) semi-decent apartment for that price range.
  • In Vancouver, there were significantly fewer listings, and the vast majority are of the Leasehold title type. There were also very few listings in Toronto for that price range, and many had very poor reviews. Apparently, one building was "dirty", "smelled so bad that I was going to puke", "one of the worst kept buildings in Toronto", "often [has] no water or heat", "[infested with] roaches, mice, bed bugs", and "feels like a movie set on how decrepit this place is". As such, it seems reasonable to exclude Toronto and Vancouver from future scraping and analysis due to lack of comparable listings.
  • This leaves Calgary, Winnipeg, and Saskatoon as being among the main options for someone looking to purchase at this price range in a somewhat densely populated urban agglomeration.
  • Further scraping should also look at other Census Metropolitan Areas with a population over 300,000, including:
    • Ottawa, ON
    • Edmonton, AB
    • Hamilton, ON
    • Kitchener/Cambridge/Waterloo, ON
    • London, ON
    • St. Catharines/Niagara, ON
    • Windsor, ON
    • Oshawa, ON
    • Victoria, BC

def extract_data(t_inner_html):
    # --extract preview img--
    pattern = r'<img\s+.*?\bsrc="(.*?)"'
    matches = re.findall(pattern, t_inner_html)
    preview_img = matches[0]

    # --extract price--
    pattern = r"\$\d+(?:,\d+)*"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_inner_html)
    price = match.group()
    price_cad = int(price.replace("$", "").replace(",", ""))

    # --extract address-
    pattern = r'data-binding="innertext=Address">([^<]+)'
    match = re.search(pattern, t_inner_html)
    address = match.group(1)

    # --find number of beds/baths--
    pattern = r'data-binding="innertext=NumberVal">([^<]+)'
    matches = re.findall(pattern, t_inner_html)

    # search parameters filter out 0 beds/baths
    num_bedrooms = matches[0]
    num_bathrooms = matches[1]

    return preview_img, price_cad, address, num_bedrooms, num_bathrooms

df["data"] = df["inner_html"].apply(lambda x: extract_data(x))

df["preview"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[0])
df["price"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[1])
df["address"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[2])
df["bedrooms"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[3])
df["bathrooms"] = df["data"].apply(lambda x: x[4])

# drop duplicates in address column
df = df.drop_duplicates(subset="address", keep="last")

def convert_to_int(t_val):
    """Clean up actual count of beds/baths - eg. (2+1)->3"""
    try:
        x = int(t_val)
    except ValueError:
        x = int(eval(t_val))
    return x


df["bedrooms"] = df["bedrooms"].apply(lambda x: convert_to_int(x))

def find_monthly_fees(t_str):
    pattern = r"\$(.*?)\s*\((?:CAD)?\)"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_str)

    if match:
        price = match.group(1)
        return price
    else:
        return 0


def return_frequency_of_fee(t_str):
    pattern = r"\(CAD\)\s*(\w+)"
    match = re.search(pattern, t_str)

    try:
        word = match.group(1)
    except AttributeError:
        word = "N/A"

    return word

def convert_to_square_feet_int(x):
    if pd.isnull(x):
        return x
    elif "sqft" in x:
        return float(str(x.replace("sqft", "")))
    elif "m2" in x:
        return float(str(x.replace("m2", ""))) * 10.76391042
    else:
        return float(x)


df["sqft"] = df["Square Footage"].apply(lambda x: convert_to_square_feet_int(x))

def get_value(string, header):
    lines = string.split('\n')
    for i in range(len(lines)):
        if lines[i].lower() == header.lower():
            if i < len(lines) - 1:
                return lines[i+1].strip()
            else:
                return None
    return None

def get_values(string):
    headers = ['Heating Type', 'Appliances Included', 'Parking Type', 'Features', 'Square Footage', 'Cooling', 'Flooring', 'Architecture Style', 'Maintenance Fees Include', 'Total Parking Spaces', 'Amenities Nearby', 'Community Features', 'Style', 'Exterior Finish', 'Basement Type']
    values = {}
    for header in headers:
        value = get_value(string, header)
        if value is not None:
            values[header] = value
    return values

import re


def find_numbers_in_brackets(t_str):
    result_list = []
    # Define a regular expression to match numbers within brackets
    pattern = r"\((\d+)\)"

    # Find all occurrences of the pattern in the text
    matches = re.findall(pattern, t_str)

    # Print the extracted numbers
    for match in matches:
        result_list.append(match)

    if len(result_list) > 0:
        return result_list[0]
    else:
        return np.nan

def return_parking_type_dict(text):

    # Define the list of keys for the dictionary
    keys = [
        "Other",
        "Garage",
        "Heated Garage",
        "None",
        "Parking Pad",
        "Visitor Parking",
        "Rear",
        "Gravel",
        "Carport",
        "Indoor",
        "Surfaced",
        "Underground",
        "Parkade",
        "Open",
        "Stall",
        "RV",
        "Oversize",
        "Street",
        "Covered",
        "Inside Entry",
        "Tandem",
        "No Garage",
        "Interlocked",
        "Detached Garage",
        "Attached Garage",
        "Parking Space(s)",
    ]

    # Initialize the dictionary with all keys set to 0
    result = dict.fromkeys(keys, 0)

    # Check each key in the text and set its value to 1 if present
    for key in keys:
        if key in text:
            result[key] = 1

    return result

All variables

def corrdf_to_3col(num_df_default_corr):
    num_df_default_corr_us = (
        num_df_default_corr.where(
            np.triu(np.ones(num_df_default_corr.shape), k=1).astype(bool)
        )
        .unstack()
        .reset_index()
    )
    num_df_default_corr_us.columns = ["var1", "var2", "corr_str"]

    num_df_default_corr_us_clean = num_df_default_corr_us.dropna(
        how="all", subset=["corr_str"]
    ).sort_values("corr_str", ascending=False)
    return num_df_default_corr_us_clean


corr_df = corrdf_to_3col(df.corr())
corr_df["abs_corr_str"] = abs(corr_df["corr_str"])
corr_df = (
    corr_df.sort_values("abs_corr_str", ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True).copy()
)

# export for manual analysis, categorization
corr_df.query("abs_corr_str >= 0.5").to_excel('corr.xlsx',index=False)

Notes, Comments, Questions

Apartments

  • Apartments with monthly maintenance fees will likely cover water fees. Strength: 0.78
  • Apartments usually have underground parking. Strength: 0.78
  • Most apartments with monthly maintenance fees covers heat fees. Strength: 0.7
  • Most apartments with monthly maintenance fees will cover property management fees. Strength: 0.68
  • Many apartments with monthly maintenance fees will cover insurance fees. Strength: 0.67
Apartments Comments/Questions
  • Per the above, despite having monthly maintenance fees, many fees are often covered, including water, heat, property management, and insurance.
  • For other building types, despite not having an explicitly stated monthly fee, there would still be an 'implicit' fee - monthly water/heat bills, labour or costs associated with property management, insurance costs, etc.
  • As such, it can be concluded that other building types that do not have an explicitly stated monthly fee are not necessarily a better deal financially. One important factor to consider is the building age, which can indicate if repairs and refurbishments will be needed in the near future.

Bedrooms/Bathrooms

  • Apartments tend to have fewer bedrooms. Strength: -0.65
  • Listings with condo/strata titles often have fewer bedrooms. Strength: -0.55
  • Many listings with underground parking have fewer bedrooms. Strength: -0.52
  • Freehold titles typically have more bedrooms. Strength: 0.64
  • Houses often have more bedrooms. Strength: 0.51
  • More square footage often means more bathrooms. Strength: 0.56
  • (Added later) More square footage often means more bedrooms. Strength: 0.5
Bedrooms/Bathrooms Comments/Questions
  • What other building types are there for freehold titles?
  • What is the correlation between square footage and number of bedrooms?
  • Average number of bedrooms/bathrooms for
    • Apartments
    • Houses
    • Freehold titles
    • Condo/strata titles

Building Age

  • Most listings with freehold titles at this price range tend to have been built earlier - i.e., the buildings tend to be on the older side. Strength: -0.67
  • Houses in this price range are typically built earlier and the buildings are on the older side. Strength: -0.61
  • Many listings with condo/strata titles feature buildings that were built more recently. Strength: 0.58
Building Age Comments/Questions
  • What's the average built_in value for freehold titles vs condo/strata titles?

  • If there are monthly maintenance fees, there will often be fewer total parking spaces. Strength: -0.58
  • Condo/strata titles often have underground parking. Strength: 0.58
  • Apartments usually have underground parking. Strength: 0.78
Parking Comments/Questions
  • One possible benefit to freehold titles is having more parking spaces - good for car enthusiasts and individuals/households that, for whatever reason, have multiple vehicles.

Side-By-Side Box Plots

mask = df["monthly_maintenance_fees"] > 0
t_df = df[mask].copy()

# filtered down for better grouping
all_maint_incl = [
    "maint_incl_property_management",
    "maint_incl_insurance",
    "maint_incl_water",
    "maint_incl_heat",
    "maint_incl_parking",
    "maint_incl_electricity",
]


def return_maint_incl(t_row):
    t_list = []
    for elem in all_maint_incl:
        if t_row[elem] > 0:
            t_list.append(elem)
    return t_list


t_df["maint_incl"] = t_df.apply(return_maint_incl, axis=1)

def convert_to_str(t_val):
    return ", ".join([x.replace("maint_incl_", "") for x in t_val])


t_df["maint_incl_str"] = t_df["maint_incl"].apply(lambda x: convert_to_str(x))
t_df["maint_incl_len"] = t_df["maint_incl"].apply(lambda x: len((x)))

t_df = t_df.sort_values(["maint_incl_len","maint_incl_str"],ascending=[True, False]).copy()
t_df["maint_incl_str"] = t_df["maint_incl_str"].apply(
    lambda x: x.replace("property_management", "property_mgmt")
)

mask = (t_df["maint_incl_len"] > 0) & (
    t_df["maint_incl_str"].isin(
        list(
            t_df["maint_incl_str"]
            .value_counts()
            .to_frame()
            .query("maint_incl_str >= 10") # at least 10 listings / data points
            .index
        )
    )
)

fig = px.box(
    t_df[mask],
    x="maint_incl_str",
    y="monthly_maintenance_fees",
    color="maint_incl_str",
    title="Side-By-Side Comparison",
    points="all",
)

fig.update_layout(
    showlegend=False,
    xaxis=dict(title="What The Maintenance Fee Covers"),
    yaxis=dict(title="Monthly Maintenance Fee"),
)
fig.show(renderer="iframe_connected") # figure_30.html

Notes on Side-by-side Comparison

  • Per the above mask, if there are insufficient (less than 10) listings with a certain combination, they were excluded.
  • Not all elements are included in the all_maint_incl for simplicity/better grouping.
  • The combinations were pretty much as expected - more items covered typically means higher costs.

Part Eight: Conclusions and Recommendations

Main Recommendation

  • My main recommendation for someone looking to purchase a home in the $300,000 price range in Canada would be to consider purchasing a condo in Calgary, Edmonton, Winnipeg, or Saskatoon, rather than a freehold title or house.
  • This is aimed more towards single individuals and childless couples that want to live in a relatively urban/sub-urban and well-populated metropolitan area with access to amenities, transportation, and employment opportunities.
  • Condos are typically smaller than single-family homes and may not offer as much space for families with children. Therefore, families with children may prefer to purchase a larger home or freehold title, which provides more space and privacy.
  • However, condos can be a great option for single individuals, couples, or retirees who want to downsize from a larger home or want to live in a more urban environment where amenities are within walking distance. Condos also offer shared amenities and community living, which can be particularly appealing to people who want to build social connections and enjoy a low-maintenance lifestyle.

Supporting Point 1 - Affordability

  • The number of bedrooms and bathrooms in condos are fewer than houses, and having a smaller space can also mean lower utility bills and maintenance costs.
  • Properties with condo/strata titles tend to be newer than freehold titles, with the median property being built in 2005, compared to 1955 for freehold titles. As such, while monthly fees may be higher in the short term for condos, in the long term, houses can be much more costly due to repairs, maintenance, refurbishments, etc.
  • This means that condos are less likely to require repairs or refurbishments, and may be more energy-efficient, resulting in lower utility bills. Additionally, monthly maintenance fees for condos are explicit and cover a range of expenses, providing more certainty in terms of fees and bills.

Supporting Point 2 - Convenience / Lifestyle

  • Condos are typically managed by a condominium corporation or homeowners' association, which is responsible for maintaining common areas and exterior elements such as roofing, siding, windows, and landscaping. This means that condo owners have less responsibility for maintenance and repairs compared to homeowners with freehold titles, who may need to handle these tasks themselves. The low-maintenance lifestyle offered by condos can be particularly appealing to busy professionals or retirees who want to spend their time on other activities.
  • Condos typically offer low-maintenance living, as building maintenance, landscaping, and snow removal are often taken care of by the condominium corporation or homeowners' association. This can be a great option for people who don't want to spend time and money on home maintenance and repairs.
  • Apartments/condos often have underground parking, which is a convenient and secure option for car owners.
  • There are several other benefits to living in a condo:
    • Location: Condos are often located in desirable urban or suburban areas with access to public transportation, restaurants, shopping, and entertainment. This can be a great option for people who want to live in the heart of the city and enjoy all that urban living has to offer.
    • Amenities: many condos offer shared amenities such as fitness centers, swimming pools, and outdoor spaces, which can be expensive to own and maintain in a single-family home. Shared amenities and community living can enhance the overall quality of life for condo owners.
    • Security: Condos often offer security features such as keycard access to the building, CCTV cameras, and on-site security personnel, which can be particularly appealing to people who live alone or travel frequently.
    • Community: Condo living offers the opportunity to build a sense of community and social connections with neighbors, which can be particularly valuable for people who are new to a city or looking to downsize.

Supporting Point 3 - Investment Potential

  • With Canada's Immigration Levels Plan 2023-2025, there will likely be a sharp increase in the number of immigrants in the coming years, predominantly to Toronto and Vancouver, leading to increased housing costs in these areas.
  • Therefore, purchasing a condo in Calgary, Edmonton, Winnipeg, or Saskatoon could be a smart investment as these cities are likely to see increased demand for housing as well, but not as extreme as Toronto/Vancouver. As such, the initial investment required won't be as high, but the value of the property is likely to appreciate with time, with less maintenance/repairs required.
  • Location is key when it comes to value - the value of a house in a less favourable location will likely not appreciate as much as the value of a condo in a more favourable location.
  • Condos can be a good investment opportunity for people looking to build equity in a property over time. As the population of Canada continues to grow, particularly in urban areas, demand for housing is likely to increase, which could drive up condo prices. Condos are also a good option for people who want to enter the real estate market but cannot afford a newer single-family home or freehold title.
